hackathon-description-text: This October 17-18, over 600 top college hackers from around the country will gather at the University of Washington to build the next generation of innovative software and hardware hacks.
hackathon-eligibility: Only students who have applied and have been accepted can submit projects.
hackathon-requirements: Any software or hardware hack is welcome. Please add a description of what the hack is, add a link, video, screenshots etc that can go along.
hackathon-rules:
Only teams comprised wholly of eligible participants that submit their hacks to this DevPost, and then go on to demo their hack at the DubHacks expo can win prizes.
- YOU MUST BE AT DUBHACKS TO WORK ON A PROJECT FOR SUBMISSION
- You cannot work on your project before the event begins
- You cannot steal another team's source code
- The decision of judges is final for determining prizes and awards
- Please comply with all instructions from DubHacks organizers

hackathon-prizes.prize-content: All expense paid trip to Facebook's Global Hackathon Finals at their Menlo Park, CA Headquarters on November 18th - 20th.
hackathon-prizes.prize-title: Best Use of Facebook API (or Best Overall)

hackathon-prizes.prize-content: $1,000 in free credits to each team member
Full access to next year's tech conference
Disney Infinity 3.0 Star Wars Saga Bundle
Exclusive DubHacks frisbees and shot glasses

hackathon-prizes.prize-title: Best Domain Name Registered with Domain.com (MLH)
Most Innovative Use of Data by GE Digital

hackathon-judging-criteria.judging-criterion:
Judge By:
Originality / Innovation
Technical skill
Design / User experience
General impressiveness

Don’t judge by:
Usefulness
Business potential, viability, sustainability
Team skillset and hacker credentials (i.e. “we’re Thiel fellows and ex-Googlers”)
